Hi InMoov's fan,
This is a derivative of the RobRingV3 design to replace the servos' actuators of the InMoov's hand. Here at the Funlab (http://funlab.fr) we searched for an easier way to fasten and fine-tune the tendons(fishing braid) to the servos. So we successfuly tested a solution using 2 washers with bolt and nut to fasten one tendon, and then we modified the design of the RobRingV3 to implement that solution. With this design it is possible to re-adjust your settings because no glue is used. The actuator's middle hole has been enlarged compared to the original RobRingV3 to fit our servos (MGR996R) Hope you'll like it !
Comments are welcome ! (For french readers,more informations on our wiki : http://funlab.fr/funwiki/doku.php?id=projets:construction_du_robot_inmouv )

For one actuator, there are 4 M3 bolts and 4 nuts :
  • 2 bolts and nuts to fasten the 2 tendons corresponding to one finger
  • 2 others to store a little extra fishing braid to allow later adjustements and also for easy handling when you pull on the braid before fastening it..
  • 1 little rubber band, to avoid the extra fishing braid to unwind.
    • Before puting the cover on top of the forearm, make sure that no bolts are touching the inside of the cover, You might have to screw a little more the bolts (choose short one's), and you also might need to file the inside of the cover at some spots. The last picture shows (in red) the best way to wind the tendons on the bolts. (For french readers,more informations on our wiki : http://funlab.fr/funwiki/doku.php?id=projets:construction_du_robot_inmouv )

description.text:
A working (toy) stethoscope.  
This model does work and I was able to faintly hear my own heartbeat with it but can't really see this taking off to supply the hospitals of the world...

Print either the one-piece or diaphraghm + bell and glue/acetone together.  Two versions are supplied because the supports are quite hard to remove on the one piece version.  I also brushed mine with acetone to plug up any holes.  
Print a copy of the membrane and glue thin foil or paper to the side that isn't flat.  Once dried secure the membrane inside the diaphragm with blu-tak and the foil/paper facing out.  
Attach plastic tubes to the outlets on the bell.  You should now have a working stethoscope, so stick the tubes in your ears and see if you can hear a heartbeat.  
Openscad source file is provided so you can adjust for different size tubing, etc.  The STL files assume ~1CM diameter tubes.
Ashaman created this and I am uploading to share with another group.

description.text: This feeder, which I made over 2 months, works to feed my betta fish Crucio and other fish who have owners like myself that forget to feed them. The feeder rotates every 12 hours to feed the fish about 5-7 pellets of food. Crucio is a male betta fish that stole my heart on Christmas Eve. Crucio lives a very simple life but I tend to forget to feed him. I love Crucio so much but I am often at volleyball practice or at weekend-long volleyball tournaments and cannot feed him. My traveling is the reason that I want Crucio to have an automatic fish feeder so he does not have to go hungry when I am away at volleyball tournaments.

Step 1: The Materials

First collect all of the materials. The materials you will need are

  • One Continuous Servo with a 23 mm diameter circle attachment
  • Arduino Uno
  • 9V Battery Pack (that can attach to the Arduino)
  • 3 wires (preferably black (ground) , red (power) and green/yellow/blue)
  • Velcro
Step 2: The Wire

Attach red, black and green yellow wire to the Servo. Then attach the green wire to import hole 9. The red wire should go into power hole and the black wire should go into the ground hole.

Wire Connections Step 3: The Battery

Insert the 9V battery into the battery pack and attach the battery pack to the Arduino but make sure the battery pack is switched to the off position as to not train the battery.

Step 4: The Code

include

Servo myservo; // create servo object to control a servo
// a maximum of eight servo objects can be created

int pos = 0; // variable to store the servo position

long FISHFEEDER = 43200000; // 12 hours between feeding
long endtime;
long now;

void setup()
{

myservo.attach(9); // attaches the servo on pin 9 to the servo object

myservo.write(0);
delay(15);

}

void loop()
{
now = millis();
endtime = now + FISHFEEDER;

while(now < endtime) {
myservo.write(0);
delay(20000);
now = millis();
}

for(pos = 0; pos < 180; pos += 1) // goes from 0 degrees to 180 degrees
{ // in steps of 1 degree
myservo.write(pos); // tell servo to go to position in variable 'pos'
delay(15); // waits 15ms for the servo to reach the position
}
for(pos = 180; pos>=1; pos-=1) // goes from 180 degrees to 0 degrees
{
myservo.write(pos); // tell servo to go to position in variable 'pos'
delay(15); // waits 15ms for the servo to reach the position
}
}

Upload the code onto the Arduino.

Code Credit: https://www.instructables.com/id/Arduino-Fish-Feeder/

Step 4: The Container and Top

3D print the container body and the top. Then insert the Arduino, The Servo and the battery pack inside of the container body. The Servo should be slightly on top of the Arduino so that the Servo can fit inside of the hole in the top. Attach three strips of velcro to the bottom of the container

Step 5: The Bottle

3D print the bottle but in order for the bottle to be attached to the Servo you have to take off the attachment and put it in the bottle while it is printing. Around 26% is the correct time to put the attachment in so that the print will not fail.

description.text:
A 3d printable toy locomotive designed to work with the very common wooden track you see all over the place.

I wanted to design some additional toy trains, since even though there are a number of track objects, there are few actual printable trains. In other designs I've seen too, they use a hook and loop system over the magnets. I've designed mine to use 5mm magnet balls, like the old buckyballs. It seemed reasonable that these would be easy to come by, and they seem to work well. Since I'm using a magnet ball too, it allows the ball to rotate and change polarity as needed; an issue I've observed on the mass produced toy wooden trains.

The train in it's current form will need to be glued together and let to set before you start throwing it around. The couplers, I printed at .1mm height, and everything else is at .2mm height. Study the attached image showing the pieces color-coded, to see how the engine should go together. It should be pretty straight forward.

description.text:
Fed up sitting a great big ATX PSU next to your Prusa? Fit a remote switch so you can move that ugly box out of the way.

If you were competent to rewire your ATX supply you should be able to insert this switch in the green power on wire. If you are unsure about electrics DO NOT DO THIS as if the wires come adrift inside the PSU you could end up with mains on the switch box or worse.

Just another boring safety reminder: Always UNPLUG the ATX PSU before opening it up and take care. You do not want to win a Darwin Award.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

No

0.15mm

20%

Notes:

Make sure you have good adhesion or it WILL curl up at the corners - you might want to use a brim

1 - The Switch

Use a rocker switch that is designed to fit a nominal 1/2 x 1" (~12.5 x 26mm) panel cut out, select a type with two clips at each end. It should simply clip into the lid.

2 - Wire it Up

Use a low-current twin wire, soldered in place. Tie a knot just down from the switch, then thread the wire through the hole in the box. The other ends of the wire need to be spliced into the green 'PWR ON' lead that is otherwise connected to black (GND) when customising an ATX power supply.

Make sure to use heatshrink to insulate the joints inside the PSU "or you will inevitably die".

3 - Fitz Da Bitz

Use two M3 by 20mm cap head screws to fit the two parts of the switch box together. The box will clip onto a standard 6mm thickness Prusa main frame.

You can now tuck your ATX PSU out of sight, but make sure you don't block the fan holes.

Introduction

Scavengers is a table top miniature war game for fighting skirmishes with fantasy/steampunk figures. Two players fight a small scale combat with five to ten miniatures on each side (a hero and your henchmen). The game is easy to learn and play, though there is enough depth that it will take time and experience to master.

The game was designed around three core premises.

a) You can download our 3D models or use any miniatures in their collection. Thus, the game is not specifically designed to any particular manufacturer or company. But if you like to help the game dev, please download our models! (They are free and paid...)

b) It is important that the miniatures on the table be the focus of the game. In the end, miniature gaming should be about miniatures (and fun!)

c) A large background - We´ll develop new units, histories and game scenarios. But we need your help, sending suggestions to improve the game!

I hope you like our game and have fun! Ahh, an important thing: this is the basic core rules, our idea is releasing other books to improve the game!

The pillar can be clamped to a Maerklin H0 M-track.
The pillars are best placed close to the connection of two tracks. This avoids tilting over the pillar when the train passes.
It worked well for me with a set of pillars differing in height by 1 cm.
The OpenSCAD file allows you to set the height of the bridge pillar. The variable x at the beginning of the file is the height in mm. The print was made on an Ultimaker in PLA. On request I added more stl-files. I myself printed the pillars up to a height of 8 cm. Please let me know whether the higher pillars work as well.

title: LM2596 & LM2596S Buck Step-Down Module Holder

description.text:
Just got a new LM2596 Buck Step-Down Module and I decided to create a nice holder for it. I also included the SLDPRT file in case you want to make your own changes in Solidworks.

You just need to print 2 of these and slide them on either side of the module. The holes are for M3 screws, but are not really needed, since I designed it to hold the thing pretty tight.

You can put some double sided adhesive tape on the feet in case you want to secure it in place.

The curvature on the back side of the holder is to account for the soldering points of the terminal, and are deep enough in case you want to solder your own wires to the back of the module.

A remix of Tech2C's design using no printed parts, my answer to classic Catch 22 when it comes to building a 3D printer with no access to one for the usual printed parts.

I settled on the SCS10Uu bearing housing as a key to bolting all the aluminium pieces together.
I used about 1M of 25 x 12mm al bar and 1.8M of 3mm thick 25mm eq angle.

I used opposing hooks for a display bracket and a chopped down angle d=grinder key for the spool holder.
Plenty of challenges, first component failure was the psu power plug on a cheapo RAMPS board which I then upgraded to some spare screw terminals.
I'm also a great fan of heatsinks on power mosfets as can be seen in the RAMPS pic.

For the complete why, what and how of what i did, head on over to the build instructable.
